                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote type="marginal"><lb/><label>Ruling:</label> Margins ruled in gold,
                        outlined with thin single interior and double exterior black lines,
                        surrounded by single vermillion interior and exterior dark blue single
                        lines, and a further single lines of the latter along the perimeters of the
                        pages.</decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <lb/><label>Inscriptions:</label>
                     <list rend="bulleted">
                        <item> The <locus from="ib" to="ib">first right flyleaf b side (f.
                              ib)</locus> bears bookseller's notes and a price of <q xml:lang="en"
                              >£10.0.0.</q>. </item>
                        <item> The <locus from="iib" to="iib">second right flyleaf b side (f.
                              iib)</locus> bears the number and title <q xml:lang="en">Nº 103
                              Dabistan</q>, which albeit unsigned comports with the hand of
                              <persName role="ins ato fmo" key="person_44733962"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/44733962">Sir Gore Ouseley </persName>. </item>
                        <item>A subsequent owner attempted to clip off <persName role="ins fmo"
                              key="person_44733962" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/44733962">Sir Gore
                              Ouseley</persName>'s autograph on the top-right corner of folio <locus
                              from="1b" to="1b">1b</locus>, but part of it remains. </item>
                     </list>
                     <label>Bookplates:</label> The <locus from="Inner_back_cover"
                        to="Inner_back_cover">left pastedown</locus>: <q xml:lang="en">Bibliotheca
                        Lindesiana</q> with pencilled shelfmark <q xml:lang="en">I/A</q>, and <q
                        xml:lang="en">Bland MSS No. <hi rend="strikethrough">411</hi></q>. </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1775">
                        <p>Covered in a hybrid British-Indian style in the <placeName cert="high"
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208"
                              >Indian subcontinent</placeName>, possibly in <placeName cert="medium"
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7030776">Calcutta
                              (Kolkata)</placeName> for former owner <persName role="ins ato fmo"
                              key="person_44733962" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/44733962">Sir Gore
                              Ouseley</persName>.</p>
                        <p>Sewn at two stations, unsupported, with sewn endpapers of similar stock
                           as the text, edges trimmed, with chevron endbands twined in pink and
                           green silk threads over round cores at <locus from="Head" to="Head"
                              >head</locus> and <locus from="Tail" to="Tail">tail</locus>. Covered
                           in full, highly polished dark brown goatskin
                           <material>leather</material>, over <material>pasteboards</material> and
                           tight-backed on the <locus from="Spine" to="Spine">spine</locus>, with
                           squares at <locus from="Head" to="Head">head</locus> and <locus
                              from="Tail" to="Tail">tail</locus> (albeit the fore-edge protrudes),
                           defined joints, but without a flap (Type III binding per Déroche). Board
                           interiors lined with maroon goatskin <material>leather</material>, with
                           their excess widths put down as hinges on the first and last flyleaves in
                           order to connect the textblock to the cover. </p>
                        <decoNote type="binding">Boards decorated with recessed central mandorlas,
                           pendants, and corners <material>paper</material> onlays blocked in gold
                           with large floral designs featuring octafoil blossoms and seratted
                           leaves, with smaller quatrfoils in the pendants.Central decoration
                           connected by a single vertical line ruled in ochre, with double lines of
                           the same connecting the cornerpieces and again along the board
                           perimeters. Spine subsequently fully gilt by a British binder for
                              <persName role="ins ato fmo" key="person_44733962"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/44733962">Sir Gore Ouseley</persName>, in
                           keeping with other volumes that he had similarly rebacked, albeit in this
                           case left untitled. Divided into six panels by thick single fillets, with
                           thin rope, circle-and-dart, and single fillet lines, and large arabesque
                           quatrefoils in the centress.</decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>382</height>
                              <width>231</width>
                              <depth>45</depth>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>Handle binding with caution. In fair condition with the exteriors
                           scuffed, abraded, and insect damaged.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>Completed by <persName role="scr">Ẕū-al-Fiqār ‘Alī</persName>, probably in
                     the <origPlace ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208"
                        key="place_7000208">Indian subcontinent</origPlace> on <q xml:lang="en"
                        >Wednesday 22nd Safar</q>, but he omits the year; however, it probably dates
                     to the <origDate cert="medium" calendar="#Gregorian" from="1699" to="1801">18th
                        century</origDate>.</origin>
                  <provenance><p>Formerly owned by <persName role="ins fmo" key="person_44733962"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/44733962">Sir Gore Ouseley
                           (1770–1844)</persName>, which while unsigned, the inscription on folio
                           <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> comports with his hand and numbering
                        as found on other volumes from his library.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently listed for sale by <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781"
                           >London</placeName> firm of <persName role="bsl"
                           key="person_1555163159917201640001"
                           ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/1555163159917201640001/">Howell and
                           Stewart</persName> in their <date from="1827" to="1828">1827–1828</date>
                        catalogues.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Subsequently acquired by by scholar <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/" key="person_20108923">Nathaniel
                           Bland (1803–1865)</persName> for his library at Randalls Park, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011735" key="place_7011735"
                           >Leatherhead</placeName>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>After Bland's death, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781"
                           >London</placeName> bookseller <persName role="bsl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/" key="person_5679225">Bernard Quaritch
                           (1819–1899)</persName> sold his oriental manuscripts to <persName
                           role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058"
                           >Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812–1880)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866-06">June, 1866</date>, paid in two
                        instalments of £450 and £400, and then moved to <orgName
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/295427552" key="person_295427552">Bibliotheca
                           Lindesiana</orgName> at Haigh Hall, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010384" key="place_7010384"
                           >Wigan</placeName>. </p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName type="standard" role="dnr"
                           key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands
                           (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901"
                           >1901</date> from <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName type="standard" key="person_f6379"
                           change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908">1908</date> to the <orgName
                           type="corporation" role="rps" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John
                           Rylands Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
